JOY TO THE GELATINOUS— for the love of jello/ gelatin salads, desserts and entrées— 

I think it’s delightful that no matter the culture, or era, humanity took gelatin—something quite simple, affordable and attainable and elevated it into sculpted culinary art.

💗 Optional reading 💗
*you will not be graded on this information 

- Jello salads were created to keep salad tidy and in place on the plate. “salad at last in control of itself,” states Laura Shapiro, author of Perfection Salad 

- Jello/ gelatin helped stretch the grocery budget. Food encased in jello will go further. I think this is especially true of Aspic or meat jelly.

- Speaking of “meat jelly”, the origins can be traced back to a 10th century Arabic cookbook.

- Jello became really popular during hard times, when women had less time to cook and clean up. 

- Meat jelly and fruit jelly are eaten around the world, from Jamaica to Russia, most cultures have their own version of gelatin salads, desserts and entrées. To view more recipes, ideas  and jelly art, visit my @pinterest folder marked “jelly snacks”.

Final thoughts: what intrigues me most about gelatin and jello is that it’s primarily a working class food. That explains why I ate a lot growing up (meat and dessert), my fathers favourite was Kholodets or head cheese. 

The under the sea salad is may fave. @jello salads are best served after the main course. “Try listening to trance” 🖤 I’m on a call with my best friend @rosevictoriawilliams Rose is a brilliant artist. A fellow creative. Being creative brings joy— hard earned joy. Joy with a side of mental meandering and intensity. 🖤 Trance can settle a creative mind. Empower it. I’m forever indebted to the genres artists for their melodic symphonies. I always felt a connection to one artist in particular. Perhaps, it was our chance meeting many, many, years ago. —I’m walking home from “work” — work in a new world, full of music, fashion, parties. A car pulls up, “What’s on your bag?” the passenger hanging out the widow asks. I smile and unsling the bright backpack “dinosaurs. I like the stegosaurus the best” I offer a drop of additional information, as the stranger intrigues me and feels safe. A massive smile erupts on the gentleman’s face “your outfit is dope”. Now I’m smiling “thanks!! I made it myself!! The fabric was just two dollars a meter! The shoes are from the Salvation Army- it’s so hard to find a shoe…” “that balances?” “Yes that’s it”, “I don’t want to look precious”. He laughs, “come here”— a uniquely defined hand twists out window. “This is for you” the hand, looking like the base of a wise banyan tree, drops a compact disc into my grateful palms. I ask no questions, an enthusiastic “thank you” is chirped from my happy face. “Remember, YOU are the art”— as the man speaks, his long index finger extends and he tap-tap-taps his temple. The car drives away. At home I immediately put the CD on. I’m mesmerized. I love it. The CD cover is simple paper. A list of tracks, some names - no art. Yet. A year later they are a hit. I kept that CD. I kept that memory. Music loving friends have begged for it. Offered money. No way. In that chance meeting, the man, his name, Maxi Jazz, in that chance meeting I was given the confidence to be me. Quirky me. Creative me. Not fitting in me. Interestingly, over the years I lost site of that girl. Then,she started forcing her way back. I took the summer off this year— to bring her home. My soundtrack for that journey? Trance- in particular Faithless. 🖤 Rest in forever peace Maxi Jazz #maxijazz #faithless #trance

We all know who Bruce Lee was— is. Bruce Lee is forever. Coining Lee a pop culture icon, feels cheap. I have the feeling nothing cheap ever touched Bruce Lee. Affordable yes, cheap never. I can’t even call his personal style “fashion”, that feels contrived. Fashion is contrived. Innate style comes from the mind, rather than external sources. In Bruce Lee’s case, it seems to come from body and mind. His body is perfection. His smile, the greatest accessory—ever. From his youth, to Hollywood/ Hong Kong cinema glory, his sense of style, never wavered. Bruce Lee understood fabric, it’s interaction with body and movement. From simple tanks, to a tailored three piece suit, paired with a Cuban heel— everything, feels natural. An extension of Lee— “bil jee”. Slide two, the Lurex top, it’s second nature. Lee makes sweat look chic. His ability to know exactly where a waist should hit, to his healthy respect for patina (note his well worn belt) —Lee gets it. There is never a lapse. Never a moment of discomfort. The way he bites his sunglasses, dipped in stability, composure and confidence… It’s a moment. My word for Bruce Lee — equanimous. I’ll have a video of Bruce Lee in my stories shortly. I just have 500 punches and 400 finger jabs to wrap up.

Candid question (legit)- how much should kids be allowed on public social media? I don’t mean their own. A follower just sent me an article about my previous post with concern that the women seeking the 1 mil followers exploits her babies/ small children. I’m wondering how parents navigate this? Truthfully, I love catching up with friends and their families— cute kids, grandkids etc on social. I never really thought about this. The kiddos in my life don’t want on social. I also get a sense when it’s a natural shared family moment, or fun video — the kids are cool with it — it feels ok. But when the kids have a camera chasing them and they seem stressed, or the parent seems to be staging a situation— it feels off. Perhaps after 15 years on camera — you can sense the difference. Or does everyone feel that? Some kids love performing. For some— they have structured public careers. I believe that’s their right. But what about those who don’t? Really little ones? My dad was an amateur photographer. A good one. I hated (actually still do) posing for a still camera. After a stern lecture from me about portraits (age nine), he switched his focus to landscape, animals and candid shots of family. Those are my favourites- the candids. I do wonder how kids, perhaps if their parents have really large followings — I wonder how this exposure will this effect them? Most kids will do whatever to keep their parents happy— that’s not healthy. Trust me. I really appreciate the women for sending me her views, and some clippings. 👋🏼I appreciate your time, voice and concern. This is very much something I should have considered. 💕 The stuffie in these shots is Cherlz. He’s 13. He got sick of being on my social media so I allowed him to have his own (private). He made a friend with another Charles online. We now share custody. Not sure how I feel about that either. 💕#childdevelopment #childhood #photostudio #kingcharles #squishmallows #squish #uglydolls #auntlife

Saturday night. I’m writing. My mind reflects. I “fact check” myself on Gmail. I laugh. Young me, is “accidentally confident”. According to my upbringing, I was to be nothing. Hammer that enough, one believes it. Hammer it on the wrong kid and you get a hardworker, a gambler, prankster, unsinkable, fearless person who might be a bit of a punk. Yes, I’m the latter. When one has nothing to lose, one may barrel into everything, with a carefree, careless approach.

There is no moral to this post. Just me, waddling over a memory. – It’s 2010, a pint-sized tyrant (exec producer) at a daytime show – let’s call her Gollum, is trashing my reputation to anyone and everyone. I’m thrown off a show I contributed to —in ways that weren’t broadcast. I should be distressed. I’m not. I’m pissed off— pissed off enough to turn my “confidence dial” up. (53% is my daily). Weeks later, I walk into an audition. Role, “co-host”. A new show, with Ty Pennington (2000’s décor guy)—my sparkle? 84%. Why? I figure, land the part, discredit Gollum. “Crazy”, as she calls me, doesn’t land roles.
 
Enter “new show”, challenge one —my appearance. Production doesn’t want me. Production and the network have an “ideal” for “co-host”, an ideal, I look nothing like. I steal the audition. I don’t get the part. Different direction, I’m told. The host has requested some information. Then the “part” is mine. If, I agree to being a brunette. “Sure whatever”—I’d say whatever to anything at this point. Imagining Gollum’s face, puckered in annoyance, is just too joyous. I agree to a wig… It’s a nice wig. Stylish, comfortable. It’s not me. Day one, I arrive with my short blonde hair. “Where’s the wig” Sally from production yells. “Yeah, sorry, felt like a cloud on my head”. I’m such a punk. “I can’t see my ideas with it on”. 

Ideas—my gold. Research, insane amounts of research and knowledge—my gold. Innate creativity—my gold. Confidence—my gold. Confidence so comfortable in its ability, I share my notes/ findings/ contacts and concepts freely—my gold. If you know me. You know. The emails I find about the host “stealing” my samples, props, research prior to me being hired—chuckles—my gold.

Here is a clip, from the film, that earned Clara Bow her famous monicker.

“It” is a 1927 American silent film directed by Clarence G. Badger and Josef von Sternberg, and starring Clara Bow. It is based on the serialised novella of the name by Elinor Glyn, who also appeared in the movie. 

The invention of the concept “It” is generally attributed to Elinor Glyn, but already in 1904, Rudyard Kipling, in the short story “Mrs. Bathurst” introduced It. — It isn’t beauty, so to speak, nor good talk necessarily. It’s just ‘It’. Some women will stay in a man’s memory if they once walk down the street.
In February 1927 Cosmopolitan published a two-part serial story in which Glyn defined It. “That quality possessed by some, which draws all others with its magnetic force. With ‘It’ you win all men if you are a woman and all women if you are a man. ‘It’ can be a quality of the mind as well as a physical attraction.”

I love this pic. Mexico. 2019. I need a vacation. Soon. I need a break from Toronto… it’s very noisy lately. This Saturday, the gentle hum of downtown was broken by a LOUD megaphone “end body shame! End body SHAME” screeching, bloodcurdling, shrieking. “NOWWWW!!!” Other megaphones chime in. Marching along. Mostly naked. Like fully. A sheer thong, here and there. I’ve been pretty “real” lately. Not contrived “victim” -marketing real. Just “human trying to get by”, real. Maybe, “go to a movie on occasion”, real. The boring type. If I was the other type, I may have joined the protest. “END BODY SHAME”! A day-glow man turns to me. He has a paper thong on. It looks like the kind you get free at the tanning salon. He’s whippet lean. I realize how different we are. I’m in workout gear. Over my shoulder I’m lugging my “find”. My “find” is a pink stand, solid metal. A beautifully fabricated fixture I picked up at the Nordstrom fixture sale. It was $25. It probably costs 2k to make. It’s heavy as all heck. Luckily, I’ve been lifting heavy, eating clean, doing runs in the sun. I got this. He stares at me. Correction, glares at me. Up and down his eyes go over my body. He steps in closer. The man next to me says “easy now bronco” (I didn’t get that till later). But for some reason… I think I’m just so sick of the yelling… I giggle, gulp. This man hates me. Why? One guess. He (at least) drops his megaphone, YOU!!!! END BODY SHAME. His eyes dart over to the man, a solid foot taller than me, strapping, glowing dark skin. END BODY SHAME! Squeal!! The first megaphone sees her comrade in distress or “trigger”, she blasts the mega phone. Then out of nowhere a squeak. A tiny squeak. The squeak gets louder. It’s a wee one. Maybe 3, hands over his ears “shut up! Shut up! Shut up! Shut up!”. The entire group of us, (We are waiting to cross Yonge street. We are a mix of shapes, sizes and shades.) We burst out laughing. Laughter. The voice of reason. The irony, isn’t shame something we feel? Yes, it can be handed to us. We don’t have to take it. Maybe the group can megaphone at home next time. Into the mirror. I’ll get heat for this post. I don’t care. I’m anti attention seeker. ❤️

Like many, I loved the original Sex in the City series. I remember watching the show in my very early twenties. I’d just returned to Oakville (small town of my nightmares) after living a brief metropolitan and fabulous single life in Miami. Of course, as one does in Miami, I’d over spent, took stylish jobs that paid little, dated some pretty fabulous men… and let my work visa expire at the most inopportune moment. Whoops. So it was back to the family home for me, I was broke. Not fun. My parents are charming at a dinner party. And strict and controlling as all hell. I’d already disappointed them by breaking up with my fiancé, a wealthy Boston law student, I dropped out of my post grad journalism program to work in fashion & at a night club in the (shock, horror!!) in the USA. They weren’t pleased. I returned home penniless and under martial law. No car, no men, no clubs, no fun. My only solace was an old TV. I snuck it up to my room from the basement and when my darling older brother popped by for a visit, he got the TV working. Days later, I found (or had found for me) a proper job. A boring job, with a creepy “touching” politician-ties boss. His clients were “husband” potential 🙄…. I was allowed to go to the gym, and that’s it— a lady must keep her figure. To escape the torture, in my room at night, I would watch Sex in the City over and over again. Plotting my next escape. My next adventure. Watching four unmarried women conquer NYC inspired me. Maybe I wasn’t so awful. Or wrong. ❤️I escaped about six months later. Started over. Found a tiny apartment, much like Carrie’s. I’ll be honest, while the Sex in the City movies were fun. They focused too much on “couples”.. same with season one of the reboot. What I loved about the original series is, it was about women, in the world, it was raw and real, with a splash of glam. It was about friendships, mistakes. It wasn’t perfect. If you have started season two of the reboot, I’d love your opinion. I feel like everything we loved about the first series is back. The acting is on point. As is the wardrobe. Thank you @sarahjessicaparker for season two. I think you may have inspired many of us, a second time around.

I’ve finally found my calling. I was confused. Till today—a light went on! As you know, in 2023, I was severely depressed. To get me well, my dear friend Gatsby, my adorable brother, & yes even Mama— they supported me enough to take a break. My sweet trainer Josh sensed I wasn’t feeling mentally well & trained me through my depression. For the first time in my life, I felt secure. I didn’t have to do it ALL myself. ❤️I ordered fiction & read it. Long walks & trips to the market led to healthy meals, made at home. As the depression started to fade, a fulfilled & more youthful me emerged. I started thinking of new ideas for a business. I took courses. Gatsby gave me a lovely offer, pick a business — I’ll back you. Diary, my mind went blank. I had fought so hard to have a career. Now blank? What people don’t realize is, & God bless them, but my family didn’t help me become a career women. In fact, while proud, they discouraged me. Why? In my mothers culture the youngest daughter is born with a purpose. We are taught the art of homemaking, entertaining, decorating, growing fruit & veggies, being a lovely host, how to sew, how to play cards…we are told we don’t like babies. There is no dowry for us. Weddings, dresses all that stuff isn’t brought up. We are created to one day take care of our parents. Yes, I went to university but my courses were selected for conversational knowledge. I wasn’t suppose to go anywhere. My problem was, at ten, I got a paper route & the first taste of financial freedom. 🤓After university, I pulled the greatest trick. I used all my homemaking training to build a career in magazines & on TV. Then covid came, & new faces took over the media, no one wanted a single homemaker. Mother jumped — move in! No! I wanted my career back. Till this break. Diary, I feel better than ever. I don’t miss a hectic career. I think all I ever wanted was freedom. Diary, I can handle a career that doesn’t break me. (Make it cute) But if I’m honest, I want to be a stay at home Grandma— one day. So Diary, I’ll need a divorcé or widower with grown children. An active fun man. I’ll look nice on his arm, handle the homemaking & we can play cards. XO- J

This is a career related post about lifestyle. 
My mentor, retail genius, Marketing Hall of Legends member, Private Label Hall of Legends member, American Marketing Associaton inductee, Don Watt, is best known for his creation of the Home Depot brand and store prototype… no; he’s best know for saving Loblaws from financial ruin, developing the PC and NoName brands.. hmm. Maybe, actually he’s best known for being the first designer to use photo imagery on a package. Or was it his design of the Wal Mart brand and superstore? Sure but what about his contributions to the Expo67 pavilion, the Canadian flag?  All his charitable financial support of @camhfoundation and OCAD? Maybe—all of the above. Don Watt was the first person to see my brain as an asset. He admired the way I’d track and predict marketable trends through a number of methods. Don loved how I’d secure a front page business article about his firm, in a city where he was pitching on the day his pitch arrived. Business people read the paper back then. I thought I had no clue what I was doing when Don hired me in 2004, Don didn’t care. He told me I get it naturally and he’d teach me the rest. Teach he did, for the subsequent five years, until Don’s death in 2009, I worked with Don and he mentored me. During that time Don sent me over 2000 emails. Notes, client case studies, thoughts and predictions. Don didn’t care that I had multiple careers. He thought that brought me insight. I remember strolling into his office with my new magazine under my arm (Chocolat magaizne was my full time job), fresh from a TV appearance on Canada AM, “great segment, I’m ordering the lamp you showed”, Geoff Belchetz said with a smile on his face. “Perfect dress, yellow”, Don added. Yellow, Don’s favourite colour- it exudes trust, value and quality. Don above all valued quality for everyone. He felt shopping on a budget should never rob a consumer of their dignity. I miss Don, a lot. In the last four years Canada changed in ways I didn’t predict and didn’t enjoy. I’m not sure how many people did. Some profited. The rest of us lost our voices. “You can’t say that” replaced “my feelings on this”. ⬇️

My transformation posts aren’t only about weightloss, or working out. They are an invitation to not judge a book by its cover. In 2016 I was 200lbs. My career was on 🔥 travel, events, jawline liposuction, expensive clothing, in spite of all of ⬆️, my knees & hips hurt. I told “friends”, over countless fancy dinners at the Polo lounge, that I was happy, loved my fuller figure. … I’m a charmer, weight gain & pain were no obstacle to my entertaining ability. I appeared happy. Fast forward to October 2022. I was very alone. Almost all of the “amazing” friends I’d met at my success height, & highest weight had disappeared. In October 2022, I was also in the best shape of my life— in my 40’s. Pretty amazing right? What isn’t amazing is that I was in training— years of psychology studies & mental toughness were being put to use. How can I make this make sense? I love my father. My father was living in Hull in WW2. He was a kid who’s father had been captured by the Germans. A kid who’s father was in the war before the war. My father didn’t know if the Dad he hardly knew was alive. My father lived in Hull. Google WW2 & Hull, you can see the devistation. 95% of the homes were destroyed. 50% of the population homeless. Hull was the most severely damaged British city during WW2. This was kept a secret for a very long time. I didn’t know. I always knew something was up with my father, the temper, the charm, the moods. In fall of 2022 I mentally & physically trained for my fathers death. Thanks to my paternal grandmother, who towards the end of her 99 year life, explained my fathers responses to war, I was able to solve him a little. I became strong enough to take on the emotions of an aging man, with dementia, scared in a pandemic. To others, they still got his charm. I took the heat. Months before he passed he was lucid & looked at me with the saddest eyes, said something about his parents. I took a chance, told him a story of how much they loved him & missed him. It was the second time I saw my father cry. He looked so relieved. Weeks later the last words my father said to me were “you are a failure”. I may be, but I’m strong. I still love my father.  #transformation

Can you pick my Grandfather out from this group? I’ll give a few hints. We don’t smoke in my family. We like to keep our looks. He’s older than the others… At this point he’s already been a soldier longer the most. He started at 14. He’s now in his early thirties. Two kids at home. This photo is from Stalag IX-B. “Happy” (his nickname) started “handling” things in WW2 prior to the war … North Africa stuff. He’s not pro-colonization, he saw a lot of things in India. He is anti-Nazi. After years in India he prefers tactics, non-violence. He’s a clever man. Reads people well. Understands how to get what he wants, what is needed. To avoid the violence. He reads the news from around the world when he can. Listens a lot. He looks at view points carefully, studies the angles. Ponders various outcomes. He’s not reactive. He watches. Learns. Thinks. Years later he’ll take his blonde moppet granddaughter for long walks through his walled medieval town just south of Scotland. He will tell her stories of India, Pakistan, Turkey, Afghanistan, Morocco, Algeria, Tunisa, Egypt, Spain, Italy (where he seems to get caught over and over again… sometimes on purpose) 😂… he will teach her geography, philosophy, biology, he will tell her to travel—alone, sing, paint, eat healthy, work out, he will teach her how to read people, scan for potential situations. He will give her copies of Bruce Lee books that show how to handle a front on attacker with a gun (without using one), he will suggest her first degree be in history and he will provide hundreds of letters of his experiences to help her. He will tell her to never sit on the fence. That you can’t please everyone. Study the outcome. Study what they stand for and most importantly never support terrorists. War is inevitable. It’s what humans do. People who say it’s senseless are privileged. Israel does not have that privelege. 💙 Can you pick out my Grandfather? Non smoking. Confident and resolute.

social_posts.post_text: The last four years of my life have included a number of road blocks. Road blocks that could have been removed had I been willing to sacrifice who I am, who I am becoming. I could have said what they wanted me to say, got in line of the pecking order, acted accordingly. Instead I stayed down and took the lumps. A lot of lumps. Lumps included being removed from broadcasts I’d contributed to for years. Friends from the “industry” turning their backs, gossiping. Some even gossiping about my mental health— suggesting I be put away for observation. Some lumps were expensive, special rates for me. So what exactly did I do to deserve the lumps? I didn’t agree with the GOV on a few things. I didn’t comply with a certain group of women in broadcast/influencing. I didn’t bow down. I stayed a supportive friend to those “they” hunted down. Mean girls don’t change. They don’t grow up. They sometimes just move into more powerful positions. Today I tend to tune out that world. Focus on my own. Go about my day. I look forward to my shifts at the gym. I’m learning the ropes, from the ground up. But don’t get me wrong, I won’t bow down, but I also won’t bow out. @timgrover suggests when you get knocked down, stay down— train, learn, grow… then when you get back up you know you aren’t going anywhere. #motivation #strength #strengthtraining #integrity

It’s darn near impossible to find a good workout partner in Toronto. In LA, it’s way easier. My roommate was always up for a Sunday AM fitness class or epic hike. People I worked for in LA would jump at the suggestion to “meet” over leg day. Even friends in other states, counties, they are always happy to book a “workout vacation”… sure in Toronto, I have a great trainer and coach, good friends at the gym or the boxing club but that still leaves weekends. For three years when friends bitched about wanting to get in shape, I offered up my weekends. For one person, who claimed to be very limited, I even offered to go swim with her. I don’t love indoor pools. She never showed up. I was being “me” in people-pleasing form. Volunteering to slow my pace, share my knowledge, make time. NOT one person showed up. That’s a lie. My nephews occasionally train with me, but they are athletes and have discipline. Then it hit me. Free = disposable. So I got a job at a gym 😄 and I start my Canadian coaching school stuff in November. I already know my niche. People whom I can unleash the real non-people pleasing me on— Mistress “FINISH IT” 😈… I have a fair bit of work before I get there. In the meantime I now hunt for a weekend training partner. No more Ms. nice guy. I want to train legs Saturday, chest Sunday. I want a friend with as much experince as me, good hygiene and who knows how to spot. And someone who won’t talk politics or gossip. It’s a narrow field. 😂 #firstworldproblems #doyouliftbro #bodybuilding #toronto

Transformation Tuesday- As a kid I was trained to be nice. No matter what. Put yourself in the other persons shoes. I think most parents teach this. Makes sense. I was very good at doing what I was told, a little too good. This isn’t always a good thing. I remember coming home after a man had exposed himself to me, I was just 15 and not seen that before. I was very upset and angry. I really wanted someone to be angry with me or perhaps punch the mans face in. Instead, I was lectured on how “he may have a problem”. I’m not kidding. Over dinner. I lost my appetite. This and other things lead to my “ok sure”, “I’ll do that”, “hi I’m a human doormat” attitude, and as one can imagine, I had some repressed angry. When I started kickboxing and boxing I was encouraged to be angry and aggressive. My amazing kickboxing coach @rashad.el_amin even got me to yell when I kicked. Prior to this, I’d never yelled at anyone— in my life. It felt so good to yell. I didn’t realize, at the time—when I started kickboxing, my brain, started to transform —along with my body. This kind of adjustment isn’t the most comforable. You look back at things and say, “hey that wasn’t cool”. You can see clearly where people used you and you just laid down for them. You can get very mad— at yourself. Luckily, another thing @rashad.el_amin taught me was the concept of “instant forgiveness”. I’m also very hard on myself. If somethings not perfect, I think it’s the end of the world. Learning to box and kick-box, is very humbling. It’s not easy. You won’t be perfect. When Rashad and I would train and I’d mess up he’d yell “instant forgiveness!! Keep going!”. It’s probably one of the best lessons in life. Speaking of life, I know it’s not easy right now, for many people, for many reasons. I hope you have a safe, suitable place to let out the pain. I can’t recommend physical activity enough. Or a scream in the forest. And if it feels like you can’t get everything or anything right, remember— instant forgiveness— keep going. @rashad.el_amin is located @foxyandfierce *in person/ online programs #transformation #transformationtuesday #weightloss #weightlossjourney #kickboxing #thenandnow #lifelessons

**this is short story about my past. 

Yesterday’s News
 
I had just landed a unique position at Chocolat Magazine, a new glossy, oversized publication from Rogers Media—Style editor, and “face” of the magazine. Previously, I’d worked at women’s magazine as the second assistant. I spent a year at House and Home, as the article’s editor. Then I moved into Public Relations, working for key business leaders including Don Watt. Working at magazines fulfilled my creative side, while irking my mental health. Publishing and media in Toronto boil over with cliques and gossips. These groups—let’s call them “Cathy’s”, while thinking they are the bees’ knees, have a narrow perspective on the world, and aren’t exactly kind. I never fit in. In working in PR, I answered directly to my CEO clients. Most of them were over the age of 60, and had been featured in Forbes, when Forbes was still Forbes. I got along with them effortlessly. At dinners we discussed the future of retail. We chatted about cities to visit, quaint towns with the best olive oil. These people, shaped my life more than they will ever know. Fast forward to me landing “style editor” at Chocolat Magazine. The “Cathy’s” buzzed and blogged, “the worst thing to happen to journalism”. A call was made to Rogers HR calling me “talentless”. Soon after starting, the former “first assistant” asked me for lunch (I paid). As our order arrived, the first assistant, pushed her elbows further on to the table, tapping her unfinished nails. Her eyes narrowed as she snarked “I don’t understand how you got this job. I mean I just don’t understand, HOW?!”, followed by a familiar, awkward laugh. Chopsticks in hand, I retrieved a gyoza, gently dipping it into the 餃子のタレ. “That’s MY SOYAY SAUCE!”, she blurted out, pulling the gyoza dipping sauce away from me and placing it next to an empty, shallow dipping dish. I responded with polite conversation, the dialogue in my head saying, “that’s how”. The world is a very big place, this past week, I reminded myself there are places you just won’t fit in. And that’s divine.

While my decorating style can be described as ecclectic-well-travelled-youthful-kitsch, my gift giving style is less busy and quite chic. I believe firmly in simplicity when it comes to gifts. Thoughtfulness is the order of the day. While the affordability of sophisticated gift-giving is a secret the upper class have relished for centuries. I’m here to share those secrets. Let’s begin.

1) Nostalgia, you may have noticed my posts about toys from our youth. Some of you may be thinking, is she ok? I’m fine 😉. Why I showcases the items is two-fold, smattered among the mainstream brands are small artisans creations. I’m tickled pink that two artisans had their items sell out! The other reason I posted nostalgic “round ups” is to bring comfort. While nostalgia will cause us to reminisce, studies show that nostalgia is a mood booster and comforts people in hard times. The reminiscing allows our minds to travel back to a time where we felt safe and protected, and perhaps visit with some people we love and miss. Nostalgic gifts ideas include a childhood toy, a well loved book or album, vintage ornaments. Many of these items can be thrifted, or shopped from your home. When it comes to wrapping, I always use the quiet rich method, a simple bow, silk ribbon or jute. My tags are affordable plain tags with a sticker initial. 

2) Time is such a lovely gift. I was volunteering this week and made some inquires to my senior citizen friends— the vote was 5 in favour 1 had a special request. What do seniors want this year? They all wanted to go for a walk with their adult children and to have a cup of tea or hot chocolate, then catch up one on one. My one senior wanted a blueberry tea (the cocktail). All the seniors said they love family time, but would like a little time with their grown “little one”.

3)For kiddos, time and crafting top the list. My young friends delight when we make holiday paper puppets. We create shows and make videos. Most paper cutouts are free online and very cute! 

4) Friend gatherings. Grab a bottle of wine, your craft supplies and get creating. Wreaths are a top trend this year and easy to make leaving time for gossip and laughs.

Want to know what’s in my fridge?

Curious to know what I eat to stay in shape?

Would you like me to share my “turn back the clock” eating secrets?

So much of how we feel and look is based on our diets. As mentioned before, a lot of my body and lifestyle changes were accidental. And many were based on budget restrictions… they ended up to be a massive silver lining. 

I grew up in a family of immigrants. We grew most of our own vegetables and traded for those we didn’t grow. We grew strawberries, raspberries, blueberries and had a number of fruit trees. (My father enjoyed splicing various fruit trees together, forever the inventor🤓). Our meat came from the butcher, where we would purchase the entire cow. Bread, soups, stews, sausages, sauces, pickles and pies were made from scratch. 

I forgot about ⬆️ when I was in my 30’s. Money wasn’t hard to come by neither was a bloated North American lifestyle. Dinners out, packaged foods and a gluttonous joie de vivre was on the menu. When I started to boxing, dinners out stopped making sense. I needed to be healthier to keep up. At the time I lived with my two Swedish roommates, who are very healthy but also extremely fun. They prepared meals a lot like my family did. Dinner was always family time with my roommates and various guests. The food was healthy and whole, and we didn’t obsess about it. We had loads of fun. Healthier cocktails were often on the menu. 

When I came home to Toronto, to lock up, I continued eating European style. I found it made me happier and it’s affordable. I also started reading more about slowing down the aging process, from the inside. 

Ok so what’s the point? Well, last month a friend asked a favour. Can I make her meals for a month (a paid gig), I jumped at the chance. She sent me a message today. She’s lost 5.5 lbs and said her skin isn’t dry anymore. I’ve asked her for a before and after. 

I’m not a nutritionist or a chef, but would you be intersted in my recipes and anti aging nibbles? I promise they don’t compromise our joie de vivre… and perhaps some of my chef and nutritionist friends will join me… if I get a proper camera 🥰… what can I say. I’m frugal, it’s the German in me.

The Talented Mr. Ripley is a movie and novel I adore. It’s the only film I watched on opening day, Christmas Day. Getting permission to go involved gifting my father the 1955 crime novel a month prior, he loved it, as I knew he would. “Go on then, enjoy”, he said as my date, a handsome northern Italian law student draped my red wool Alfred Sung swing coat over my shoulders. My date and I loved the film. It had everything we love, Italy, jazz, style, cigarettes, Aperol Spritz and sexual tension. Mr Ripley (Matt Damon) was the dark anti-hero, a closeted gay intellect who struggles with fitting in. I found his character completly understandable, relatable and yes, I even understood his serial killer side. PAUSE -I can actually hear the “gasp” of the perfect-Polly’s that read my posts, watch my every move— looking for a slip. Yes Polly, I like Tom Ripley, a serial killer. I can imagine Polly now scrambling, typing threats on my page, gathering her woke sisters to start an online doxxing “cancel”… good lord what world are we living in? I love this movie because it has everything most gay men love. That’s a world where I sit comfortably. It’s real. It’s much like Luke and Adam’s relationship on the original Dynasty. Their relationship was the first gay relationship on nighttime television. My gay male friends said they loved it because it was real, flaws and all. “It shows we are human” a good friend explaind “we aren’t a novelty or a characture”. I felt the same about Tom Ripley and Dickie Greenleaf… until today. After reading a brilliant article in Vanity Fair about the film (it’s being revisited for a Netflix series) a W magazine article popped up with the headline “The Talented Mr. Ripley Is Coming to TV—But Will He Be Gay”….

“Is it possible to present a version of Ripley whose closet case status is acknowledged more textually, or a version who grows to be more accepting of his own desires? We don’t see why it couldn’t at
least be considered. Creators would certainly risk running into criticism that Ripley isn’t exactly a positive portrayal of a queer man”

I’m tapping out. Take me back to 1999. Let the gays be gay, fabulous and flawed, after all, aren’t we all?

Shanghai Express & my Pre-code Life 

In 2012 @jefhancock and I had a pretty amazing fabrication studio on North Berendo in East Hollywood. We had two enormous units. The units, joined by a massive sliding steel door, had soaring bow truss ceilings and was home to ParkerBarrow (our creative fabrication studio). As you can see from slide eight, I could drive my car right into the space. What you can’t see is there is also a Willys Jeep, two motorcycles, the welding area, a spacious bathroom -with a claw foot tub, a chefs kitchen and my bedroom. The largest bedroom I’ve ever had. This was my side, I’m Parker (as in Bonnie Parker). On Barrow’s side (as in Clive Barrow) there was his room, his motorcycles, a proper office space, a living room and extra room to build stuff. What did I love the most about this space? The proximity to history.

@jefhancock and I would go on these epic bike rides all over downtown LA, Los Feliz, and up into the heights. On one of our first rides we passed Anna May Wong’s former residence. Anna, who starred in Shanghai Express alongside Marlene Dietrich, was an actress I loved to watch as a kid. Obviously she was well before my time. I didn’t care, I’ve always loved the pre-code films of Hollywood. The raw glamour and sinful realness. Anna May Wong, made me want to smoke. She made me want to be mysterious and sultry. Marlene as well. When their movie launched in 1932 rumours swirled of their love affair. How fabulous! Inspired by pre-code and noir films, Jef one day snapped some photos of me in our space. I used a slim cigar as a prop. I was reminded of our classic Hollywood bike rides and these images as I cued up “Shanghai Express” for tonight’s viewing party. I googled the film and read a review. Perhaps pre-code life wasn’t so “naughty”… (review is pinned in the comments). ⬇️ #precodehollywood 

*What is pre-code? Before Hollywood enforced the Motion Picture Production Code censorship guidelines, films in the late 1920s and early 1930s depicted or implied sexual innuendo, romantic and sexual relationships between white and black people, mild profanity, illegal drug use, promiscuity, infidelity, intense violence, and homosexuality.

Last night I shot out of bed. “That’s it”, I email myself, 80’s-inspired fitness—back to sleep. I pitched a TV segment on fun, healthy activities recently. I toyed with a few ideas, then—80’s—perfect! The topic fits my necessary editorial elements; fun, accessible, affordable, use what you have, shop local and I have valuable ⭐️and ⭐️for the viewer. These elements are my secret recipe for quality editorial. You’ll see them in my work on shows like Cityline and NBC California Live. I never voice harsh opinions; showcase products I don’t align with or give parenting advice. I have a gift for engaging hosts, making sure they shine. My co-hosting “shine” ability was one of the main reasons I was hired to work with Ty Pennington. This ability also landed me a contract with Cityline when the show changed hosts, my “part”? Help ease a host, with no lifestyle experience, into her new role. We had a blast.
 
Fast-forward to 2019, my editorial experience is challenged. “How many followers do you have?”, “she hasn’t worked before, but she has 1.5 million followers”. 

In 2020 a new version of media takes firm hold—click bait, victimized influencers, consumption, a few stations select me to pay them $$, while other guests aren’t charged. Cancel culture arrives with the decapitation of a friend. No investigation or jury—her limp body dragged to town square for flogging. 

I’d lost my events & fabrication business, we couldn’t weather border closures. My options? Join the party, go broke, or hustle. 

I chose the latter. I’ve worked construction, cleaned offices, sold belongings. I work at my gym, prop style, food style. Scaling back equals survival and interestingly—happiness. Eventually, tides shift. In 2024, more shows, once again, looking for the type of content I produce.
 
Recently, my nephew drove me to CTV Kitchener for a holiday special, during set up I point to a DIY holiday basket that can be made for under $10, “see this?” I say to my nephew, “I want people like your Nana to be inspired to make things, everyone deserves to feel good”. I’m back—wiser, stronger. I learned more on the way down than my entire career.
